tool.name: RegionWidth

param.name: in_features
param.dialogReference:
Input features to be used as region boundaries.

These can be any spatial features. For supplementary contours generation, the result of Region borders tool should be used.

param.name: cell_size
param.dialogReference: Cell size used for generation of region width raster. It can be selected freely, without any dependency on the input raster DEM cell size. The smaller the cell size, the more precise the region width estimation. However, extremely small values may cause long computation time. Set reasonably.

param.name: snap_raster
param.dialogReference: A raster used to snap the resulting region width raster. Width and centrality rasters must be aligned and must have the same geometry. Therefore, if a centrality raster is computed first, then it should be used as snap raster in Region width tool, and vice versa.

param.name: interest
param.dialogReference:
This parameter can be used to limit locations for which the region width will be estimated. It can be used to speed up computations, if region width only inside or outside polygons is of interest. There are three options available:

  • ALL - region width will be estimated at any point inside the envelope (extent) of the input features. Available for point, line and polygon input features.

  • INSIDE POLYGONS - region width will be estimated inside polygons. All other locations will be NoData. This mode is used during the estimation of average region width of closed supplementary contours. Available for polygon input features only.

  • OUTSIDE POLYGONS - region width will be estimated outside polygons. All other locations will be NoData. Available for polygon input features only.

param.name: mode
param.dialogReference:
Region width estimation is performed by fast external module written in C++ programming language. If for some mysterious reasons an error appears during processing, you can switch this parameter to PYTHON (which is an early implementation of the same algorithm). Remember that PYTHON option does the same, but is much slower (10 times and more). Please use it only in case when you experience some problems with execution of the tool in the standard mode.

Default value is CPP.

tool.summary:
This tool calculates a raster that gives the estimation of a free space between regular contour.

Regular contour lines and the border of the map divide the mapped area into a set of regions. Each region can potentially contain a supplementary contour line. Region width is used to (a) ensure there is enough space to place a supplementary contour and (b) identify excessively wide regions in flat areas where supplementary contour lines are included, even if they are close to the centre of the region. Since a supplementary contour can be located anywhere within a region, an estimate of region width is required for any point within a region. This is done by Region width tool using a raster-based approach.

Region width is calculated using the following algorithm:

  1. Calculate Euclidean distance raster for regular contours.

  2. Allocate a new zero-filled output raster with the same geometry.

  3. Propagate the doubledvalue of each cell of the euclidean distance raster to the output cells that are covered by the circle neighbourhood of the corresponding size. The resulting value is determined by the following rule: If a pixel is empty or has a value smaller than the doubled value of the distance raster, then its value is replaced with the doubled value of the distance raster; otherwise it remains unchanged.

A detailed description of the method can be found in the following paper:

Samsonov T., Koshel S, Walther D., Jenny B. Automated placement of supplementary contour lines // International Journal of Geographical Information Science. — 2019. — Vol. 33. — DOI: 10.1080/13658816.2019.1610965
tool.usage: For detailed information on the tool usage please see the description of its parameters.
